data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions. When you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** instead of **`Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this fails at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

This also affects `array.Reverse()` (resolves to in-place `Span` reverse instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`). Same fix pattern applies: use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` or `.AsEnumerable().Reverse()`.
